                    <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/239">Bar Hebraeus</persName>' own time (the 13th century).
                </note>
                <!-- When the work may be easily confused with other works, a disambiguation note should be provided. -->
                <note type="disambiguation">This work should be distinguished from the Arabic <bibl type="lawd:Citation">History of the Dynasties</bibl>, which reflects a similar structure but has significant differences, 
                    including some additions that may be from Islamic sources.</note>
                <!-- A content note can provide any additional information about the work's contents. -->
                <note type="content" source="#bib2501-8 #bib2501-14">Through the 12th century, this work is largely an abridgement of 
                    <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/217">Michael the Syrian</persName>'s <bibl type="lawd:Citation">Chronicle</bibl>. The portion following this is 
                    particularly valuable for its representation of events during <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/239">Bar Hebraeus</persName>' 
                    own lifetime.</note>
                <!-- A scope note can provide further information about the topical range of the work and its relation to larger works. -->
                <note type="scope">Secular world history from Creation through the 13th century A.D. Part of a larger work which also contains 
                    <bibl type="lawd:Citation">an ecclesiastical history<ptr target="http:/syriaca.org/work/2502"/>
                    </bibl>.</note>
                <!-- Incipits and explicits (note/@type="explicit") should be labeled with their language and source. -->
                <note xml:lang="syr" type="incipit" source="#bib2501-2">
                    <quote>ܐܠܗܐ ܥܕܪ ܠܡܚܝܠܘܬܝ. ܡܒܪܟ ܐܢܬ ܗܘ ܡܪܝܐ ܘܡܪܐ ܕܟܠ ܫܘܪܝܐ ܘܫܪܝܐ: ܐܢܬ ܗܘ ܩܕܡܝܐ ܘܐܢܬ ܗܘ ܐܚܪܝܐ. ܘܠܘܬܟ ܡܬܛܝܒܐ ܟܠ ܡܪܕܝܬܐ:</quote>
                </note>
                <note xml:lang="en" type="incipit" source="#bib2501-5">
                    <quote>God, help my feebleness! Blessed be Thou, Lord, and Lord of the Universe, the beginning and the end; 
